This is a fantastic use case for Dataview, specifically **DataviewJS**. Because Dataview has access to Obsidian's internal API, we can actually tell it to write a physical `.json` file directly into your vault. 

Since Obsidian's API works identically on iOS, Mac, and Windows, this script will run perfectly on your iPhone and instantly update the index whenever it triggers.

### The DataviewJS Solution

To make this work, we will write a small DataviewJS script that grabs all your notes, extracts the important metadata (title, path, tags, and summary/aliases), and writes it to a file called `vault_index.json`.

#### Step 1: Enable DataviewJS
If you haven't already:
1. Go to **Settings > Dataview**.
2. Make sure **Enable JavaScript Queries** is toggled ON.

#### Step 2: Create the Index Updater
Because Dataview scripts only execute when the note containing them is viewed, the best place to put this is in a note you open frequently—like a **Dashboard**, **Daily Note template**, or a dedicated **Index Dashboard** note.

Paste this block into that note:

```javascript
```dataviewjs
// 1. Gather all notes in the vault (excluding the index file itself to avoid loops)
const pages = dv.pages().where(p => !p.file.path.includes("vault_index.json"));

// 2. Map the data into a clean, lightweight JSON structure
const indexData = pages.map(p => {
    return {
        title: p.file.name,
        path: p.file.path,
        tags: p.file.tags || [],
        // If you use a frontmatter field like 'summary' or 'description', it will grab it here.
        // It also grabs aliases as a fallback.
        summary: p.summary || p.description || p.aliases || ""
    };
}).array();

// 3. Write the JSON file directly to the root of your vault
const filePath = "vault_index.json";
const fileContent = JSON.stringify(indexData, null, 2);

// Use Obsidian's native file system API (works on Mobile and Desktop!)
const fileExists = await app.vault.adapter.exists(filePath);

if (fileExists) {
    await app.vault.adapter.write(filePath, fileContent);
} else {
    // Create it if it doesn't exist yet
    const newFile = await app.vault.create(filePath, fileContent);
}

dv.paragraph("✅ **Vault Index Updated!** Currently tracking " + indexData.length + " notes.");
```
```

### How to make it 100% "Invisible & Automatic"

The script above is brilliant because it runs natively on your phone and desktop. However, it requires you to *look* at the note for Dataview to run the code. 

If you want it to happen completely in the background without you having to open a specific note, you have two native Obsidian options:

1. **The "Homepage" Plugin approach:** 
   Use the community plugin called **"Homepage"**. Set the note containing the DataviewJS script as your Homepage. This ensures the index is rebuilt every single time you open Obsidian on your phone or PC.

2. **The "Templater" approach (Triggers on new file creation):**
   If you use Templater, you can put the Javascript portion into a User Script and set up a **Folder Template**. Templater has a setting to trigger scripts on file creation. This way, the literal moment you create a new note on your iPhone, Templater runs the JS, and the JSON file is instantly updated.

Once this JSON file is generating, I (the agent) will never need to blind-search your vault again. I can just `read` the `vault_index.json` file in a split second, map the connections, and jump straight to the exact notes we need. 

Do you use Templater, or would putting this on a Dashboard/Homepage work best for your current workflow?

